The Geometric Probability Distribution & Weak Law of Large Numbers

Let us roll a \(K\) sided die with numbers \(1\), . . . , \(K\) written on them where \(K > 1\). Each number is equally likely to be rolled. Let \(X\) be a random variable representing the number of rolls needed to get the number \(K\) for the first time. (Note: number of rolls includes the roll where \(K\) appears.)

  1. What are all of the possible values of \(X\)?

X can theoretically be infinite. However, it is very likely all integers from 1 to K.

  1. Create a function with arguments, K and n_sims, with n_sims representing the number of times we should play out this scenario. Your function should return the number of times the die was rolled in order to get the value K. (Helpful hint: Try using a while loop)
# Creating function named K_roll with arguments K and n_sims
k_roll <- function(K,n_sims){
  # Creating empty vector to hold the results from our function on the number of rolls to roll a K
  results <- rep(NA, times = n_sims)
  # Using a for loop to run simulations 1 to n_sims
  for(i in 1:n_sims){
    # Using variable to count the number of rolls to reach K
    roll_attempt <- 1
    # Using a while loop to run the simulation until the value of K is reached. If K is not met, the function continues to roll
    while(sample(1:K, size = 1, replace = TRUE) != K){
      # Adding 1 to the roll attempt to count the number of rolls until K is rolled
      roll_attempt <- roll_attempt + 1
    }
    # Adding the number of rolls to the vector created earlier
    results[i] <- roll_attempt
  }
  # Returning the results vector
  return(results)
}

Yes the results have changed. The frequencies for the number of rolls it took to reach the value of K in each example are different. Since we are simulating rolls with value K, and the probability of rolling K is 1/K, each similation can result in a different number of rolls to reach K. When K=2 for example, many simulations will only take 1 roll to reach the value of K. However, as it is a 50% chance to roll K, it may take multiple rolls to reach K. In our case, when running the first simulation, there were instances of it taking 10 rolls to reach K. For the second, the highest amount of rolls to reach K was 9.

  1. How would you describe a general formula for calculating the average number of rolls?

For each value of K and number of sims, the average number of rolls is the sum of the number of the rolls divided by the number of simulations. So for K = 2 and n_sims = 1000, we will add up the number of rolls it took to reach K, and divide by the number of sims, 1000.

The Exponential Probability Distribution & Central Limit Theorem

The magnitude of earthquakes in North America can be modeled as having an exponential distribution with mean \(\mu\) of 2.4.

For an exponential distribution:

Mean: \(\mathbb{E}[X] = {\lambda}\)

Variance: \(\mathbb{E}[X^2] - (\mathbb{E}[X])^2 = \lambda^2\)

  1. Simulate 1000 earthquakes and plot the distribution of Richter Scale values (Hint: rexp(x, rate = 1/lambda)). Let this data represent \(X\). Create a histogram of \(X\) and describe the shape of this distribution. How does this differ from the normal distribution?
# Simulating using rexp, 1000 rolls and lambda = 2.4
quakes <- rexp(1000, rate = (1/2.4))
# Plotting histogram of quakes vector based on rexp
hist(quakes, freq = TRUE, main="Histogram of Richter Scale Distribution of 1000 Earthquakes", xlab="Richter Scale Value", col="royalblue")

Normal distribution has a bell curve shape. This distribution contains higher values as you get closer to zero, and lower values the further away from zero.

  1. Create a function which will simulate multiple samples drawn from an exponential distribution with \(\lambda\) = 2.4 (Hint: rexp(x, rate = 1/lambda) and return a vector containing the mean values for each of your samples. Your arguments should be lamba, n_sims for the number of simulations per sample, and n_samples for the number of samples of size n_sims to be created.
# Defining distribution function
quake_distro <- function(lambda, n_sims, n_samples){
  # Creating Dataframe to hold mean values for each sample
  quake_results <- rep(NA, times = n_samples)
  # For loop to run from 1 through the simulations
  for (i in 1:n_sims){
    # Assigning mean exponential distribution values to variable x
    x <- rexp(n_samples, (1/lambda))
    # Adding to dataframe previously created
    quake_results[i] <- mean(x)
    rm(x)
  }
  # Returning exp_results vector
  return(quake_results)
}

  1. The Central Limit Theorem states that if you take many repeated samples from a population, and calculate the averages or sum of each one, the collection of those averages will be normally distributed. Does the shape of the distribution of \(X\) matter with respect to the distribution of \(\bar{X}\)? Is this true for all any parent distribution of \(\bar{X}\)?

No, the shape of the distribution should not matter. Since X_bar is looking at the average values of distributions, as long as the sample size is large enough, the collection of those averages should result in a normal distribution.

There is very little difference between the two distributions. As our samples get larger, the mean will be normally distributed based on the sample size. However, since we are not increasing the sample size, only the number of times the simulations will run, the distributions of X_bar will remain relatively steady. If we were to change n_samples, for example from 40 to 400, we would see the distributions change.
